            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "\"Secondary agent\" can mean different things depending on the system, but generally its role is to support, supplement, or back up a primary agent. Typical capabilities and responsibilities:\n\n- Monitoring and observation\n  - Keep watch on environment, metrics, logs, or agent behavior and report anomalies.\n- Execution of delegated tasks\n  - Perform subtasks the primary agent assigns (data retrieval, running jobs, simple actions).\n- Specialised processing\n  - Handle tasks requiring a particular skillset (e.g., language translation, image processing, verification).\n- Validation and verification\n  - Double‑check outputs from the primary agent (fact-checking, safety checks, sanity tests).\n- Error handling and fallback\n  - Take over when the primary fails, mitigate risk, or run recovery procedures.\n- Communication and coordination\n  - Relay information between agents or to humans, manage queues, or orchestrate workflows.\n- Data pre/post‑processing\n  - Clean, transform, or summarize data for the primary agent, or format results for downstream use.\n- Logging, auditing, and provenance\n  - Keep records of actions and decisions for traceability and debugging.\n- Rate‑limiting and resource management\n  - Throttle requests, manage quotas, or perform load balancing to protect services.\n- Safety and policy enforcement\n  - Enforce constraints (content policy, privacy, access control) before actions are taken.\n\nWhen to use a secondary agent\n- Complex workflows where separation of planning and execution improves reliability.\n- Systems that need redundancy or continuous monitoring.\n- Scenarios requiring specialised steps (e.g., heavy computation or external API calls) separated from decision logic.\n\nLimitations and design considerations\n- Needs clear protocols for task handoff and conflict resolution with the primary agent.\n- Permissions and environment access limit what it can actually do.\n- Latency and consistency tradeoffs — more agents can mean more coordination overhead.\n- Security and privacy must be considered if it accesses sensitive data.\n\nIf you tell me the context (chatbot system, robotics, multi‑agent planning, customer support, etc.), I can suggest a concrete set of capabilities and a protocol for how the secondary agent should behave. Which context do you mean?",
                "annotations": [],
                "logprobs": []
              }
            ]
          }
